annotation.TEXT: Alright, it's been a half dozen episodes since it was first requested, but here it is:
D'oh. Wrong house, and the game spawned me on a Bob-omb Bro., which is totally fair, which I'm totally not being sarcastic about. At least killing them again will get me more flowers.
No, I guess not. I see a Yoshi coin over there, and I could do the pass-through-floor glitch to reach it...
Note: There was a vote for a Super Mario Galaxy video that I overlooked by accident.
Demo count: 13
Ve şimdi, gülünç hız bonus oyunu!

...You've gotta be kidding me... Seriously, you're forced to be big to get past these turn blocks, but you're forced to take a hit if you emerge from the chimney of the previous house while you're big, which you need to do to carry a shell out of the house. ARGH!!!
Well, I guess I'll proceed onward with the level.
I probably should've sped up this part where I go back for more mushrooms...
Yep, even Cirno can enjoy summer! (Don't know about Letty, though.)

Nope, no collision with him either. (And I'm lucky I didn't get hit by something else while trying that!) So, if you ever lose all of your flowers during these bosses, you'll get stuck in an unwinnable situation (which is kinda lame).
Alright, I've now gotten five Yoshi coins in this level! But, I'm not quite done here yet...
Oh, and just note that I can still normal stomp things while I'm in this floating-movement state, as I'll show on one of these little yellow guys.
Whoa, new map. Well, there's the Yellow Switch Palace...
Demo count: Still 12. (No change, because I didn't actually die.)
Well, I didn't notice this until I was in the middle of annotating the previous episode, but the Yoshi coin here reappeared when I left the house and then returned to it.
In here are some mushrooms, and a Chuck practicing his pitching in way too cramped of a space.
I had a few theories as to why that occurred. Maybe there's actually two practically identical rooms, and the one I enter depends on whether I use the door or chimney.
Aw, nuts! I must've been out of practice, since it's been so long...
Wm, yb raino!
Whoa, I almost let myself get squished there. That would've sucked.
Hmm... It appears that I just pass through the big guy without even colliding with him. So, there's our answer. You can't stomp them, because you can't even touch them.
Oh, man. It's another one of those "X" signs. I'm guessing the ON/OFF switch I need will be in this house, and that I'll need this shell to hit it.
So, I just showed that I can't stomp the virus bosses or Dr. Mario.

Umm... Correct me if I'm wrong, but you could shell-kill Ptooies in SMB3, right? If so, then this representation of Ptooie here is totally inaccurate. (But, this might be a good thing in a way, so that you don't accidentally lose your shell to them.)
But, if that's the case, then the Yoshi coin won't reappear a third time.
Ah, finally! A regular goal where I can get some bonus stars! ("It's been 3000 years...")
Goal tape average so far: 517 / 16 = 32.313 stars each.

Oh, but it did. This means that, regardless of whether this house is used for one sublevel or two, either the Yoshi coin was placed as Map16 tiles, or the item memory index was set to "Index 3 No Track".
This level has Yoshi coins, and these SMB3 Ptooie Plants. Fortunately, I can spin jump off of their spike balls.
BGM: Silent Night
No, and I... just... killed... the keyhole...
Spike is also from SMB3, BTW.
Okay, nothing in the turn blocks. And yeah, I remember missing this duder at the beginning of the bowling alley earlier.
Hello, and welcome back to SDM! Now, before I get to the voting results, there's unfinished business (such as Yoshi coins) that I need to take care of in this level...
I'm glad the Ptooies are burninatable, just like I know they are in SMB3. Also, their spike balls disappear the instant I fry them. I don't remember if that also happened in SMB3...

And if that's the case, then the rooms may have been set to different item memory indexes/indices (both of those plural forms of "index" are considered correct). Anyway, with this Yoshi coin, I am now a millionaire!

Anyway, that'll do it for today. Place your votes for whether you want me to go to Yoshi Village in Winter, YellowSwitch Palace, or whatever Christmas Buster (Normal)'s normal exit unlocks next time! To be continued... Ze!

No, it's actually a P-switch, and... while it looks like I'd need the shell here, I actually didn't, because of the pass-through-floor glitch! So, I've been lugging around this shell for no reason! At least I'll remember this for next time, since there are two exits.
Yeah, I'll just assume those coin blocks stretch all the way to the right.
Oh, if I had done the pass-through-floor glitch without first getting the flowers, I would've been trapped.
Ow. Whatever. There's flowers in this house. Speaking of this house, someone wanted to see what happens if I exit it via the chimney before I enter the computer.
Or, I could be awarded flowers for defeating all of the enemies in the room! ...Yep, these blocks are flammable and inflammable. Also, I'm doing the glitch anyway just for the heck of it.
Hitbox dissonance much, game?!
Bob-omb Bros., eh? Maybe I can blow up these ice blocks?
Bonus game average so far: 31 / 5 = 6.2 1-ups each.
Okay, I've been playing for a while now, so I don't think I'm going to go for the normal exit today. However, let's at least see where this secret exit leads...
Sacrificial horse count: 7
Okay, since I'm not carrying anything, take the door to avoid cheap hits.
But, just to be absolutely sure, I'll try to collide with the Mute City guy as well.
Someone wanted me to check if I could stomp the virus bosses coming up here...

Huh, so the game pretended to kill me there or something, but I was watching the timer, and it never actually hit zero, so maybe I simply hit a custom block that played the death music as it warped me.
Anyway, we've got reindeer that know how to use the Pokémon move Present. (However, I doubt these have any chance of healing me.)
Okay, there's the key, along with a Slow Laser Bro., which I quickly burninated.
Bye, Yoshi!
25-life combo! But wait, there's more! Because of this tiny water pit, I can make the combo as high as I want! (Time permitting, of course.)

Too bad these hidden coin blocks prevent me from doing the mind screw chimney thing again. (Actually, I could've stomped the P-switch to get past them, but I'm pretty sure I need this P-switch outside.)
BGM: DKC2 - Welcome to Crocodile Isle
Argh! Well, the game did say that I can only press Start and Select here, but I thought it would just prevent the other buttons from doing anything, not just flatout kill me.
Huh. Those aren't blocks that I can grab. Can Chuck break them?
Huh. This yellow pass-through wall and the door were not made to act like water tiles here.
Now, this is the house with the football Chuck and keyhole, right?
104-hit combo! Marvelous!
Please don't glitch-hit me...
Alright, let's go back and burn those ice blocks in that football Chuck's house.

Also, I notice that the Yoshi coin reappeared, just like in that one house in Christmas Buster (Easy). I'm not going to abuse it to get 5 Yoshi coins now, but I'll keep this in mind in case I'm unable to find 5 normally later.
Umm... It seems risky to try and stomp the Big Red gum here, so I'll wait and try to stomp the big yellow guy in the next room.

...which is lacking a space between "YELLOW" and "SWITCH" for some reason. (Likely because PYUA didn't use the slightly squished "YELLOW" text, perhaps because that text was replaced with something else.)
Huh, so is this like a bonus level or something? I'm assuming so!
Yep! Now, will this key still work, even though the keyhole is apparently killable?
No power ups in here, but there is a Shell Bro., and I'm pretty sure I'll need to take one of his shells with me.
Oh, but what about Dr. Mario himself?
Gulp!
I was tempted to go back to that first house for mushrooms again, but it's probably not worth the hassle. Okay, now can I get past this Ptooie?
Don't mind me, Chuck. I'm just here for the mushrooms. Nothing more.
However, I'm already at 99 lives, so there's no need to spend any more time comboing here. Also, hi, Yoshi!
Alright, now it's finally time for the voting results!
Alright, before I end the video, I kinda want those moons...
Okay, remember this house, with the Yoshi coin inside of it, outside of it? (Huh?)

This paradise aims to give the world comfort. It makes use of shells in various ways. Down in the cave, if you throw a shell and chase after it, you'll feel exhilarated! You can get as infinitely many 1-ups as you can handle (?), up to 99.
I have to watch out for Spikes, and their spike balls, of course.
Nope. Maybe they're blocks that I have to burninate. So, I'll need to find a flower somewhere.
Yes, it does! Huzzah! Secret exit get!
Ah, okay. You just return to the main area like usual. (Also, I forgot to show this, but entering the house through the door takes you to the same room, like you'd expect.)
Okay, someone wanted me to show that these Bucket Heads' snowflakes deal regular damage to me. (Huh. Apparently, they also reset my star-kill combo if I hit one while invincible.)

This is an automatic intro. You can't press anything but Start and Select. Select will cut the intro. The first half of this stage is basically the same deal as the Easy version. But you'll also get presents from reindeer!
Oh, man. Looks like we're going bowling today! (Assuming I can throw the "12-Pounder" Prinny properly, dood.)
Oh, come on! Okay, that is just really bad enemy placement. That hit is totally unavoidable if you're big. (Trying to quickly duck won't work, since that'll just make you reenter the chimney.)
Fortunately, there was no Santa in that chimney, and no cheap reindeer nearby either, so no chance for cheap hits that time. Alright, let's head back to that house with the killable keyhole.
Yay, more mushrooms, and a football in the groin. That's always funny, right?

Okay, to be fair, I won't grab that Yoshi coin a third time. However, I'll keep the first two I grabbed here, because I searched this level high and low, and could not find an actual "fifth Yoshi coin" that I had missed, so not counting the fact that that one reappears, I think this level is actually one Yoshi coin short of a full set.
I'm getting a reserve mushroom while I'm here, just in case.
...Oookaaay... Now what?
Push! Yep, the P-switch changes the "X" to an "O" and lets me through.
BGM: Sonic 3 - Angel Island Zone Act 1
Whoa, I wasn't expecting the present to land on that ledge there. Fortunately, it took out the Ptooie for me, and I managed to avoid letting the shell get blown up!
Bullet Bro. is gone. Oh, and if I got in here with the pass-through-floor glitch, I wouldn't be trapped, since the P-switch itself can be thrown at the green blocks to break them.
Haw, haw! Santa just got blown up by a reindeer! (Hey, that could be sung to the tune of "Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer"!)
Alright, so let's head to that Barq's Root Beer Cavern!
Okay, good. Now I can afford to take one hit and still be able to get past those turn blocks.
This is as enjoyable as a refreshingly cold Pepsi on a hot summer day. (Okay, there's your Pepsi reference during this level.)
Excellent. I got here flawlessly. Oh, and thanks to the ice physics, I'm pretty sure I can duck under those munchers without getting OMNOMNOM-ed.

Alright, so I guess this is an automatic room. Umm... I have a feeling that bringing Yoshi in here might screw this up though, but we'll see... I'm not going to touch any controls on my first play of this area, regardless of what happens.
Yeah, I'm passing through the Silence guy as well.
MOOOOOONNNSSS!!! ...Okay, calm down, SRA, and just read what this message says in the translation document...
No Yoshis because they can't handle the ludicrous speed!
Okay, I'm getting beat up here.
And, I will try to use the doors more often, but sometimes the chimneys are necessary for carrying things into or out of the houses.
Alright, that just unlocks a path back to "You're the Star!". Now, Christmas Buster (Normal) did come in second place in the voting, so I think I'll head there next.
I am curious if there's anything of value in any of these turn blocks...
Huh, there was no keyhole here last time. Alright, does this turn block perhaps contain a key?
